In article <C2F2s3.9FM@iat.holonet.net> mmurphy@iat.holonet.net (Mark Murphy) writes:
>In "A digital signature scheme secure against adaptive chosen-message
>attacks" (SIAM J. Computing April 1988) and "How to sign given any
>trapdoor permutation" (J. ACM January 1992), various authors have
>presented schemes that are more robust against forgery than straight RSA
>or other methods.  However, I haven't seen any evidence of these
>techniques being used in practice.  It seems likely that they are too
>difficult to decently implement in software, given the complicated
>signature that they create.
>
>Has anyone seen an implementation of these anywhere?
This is more theoretical than practical.  I know of no actual implementations
of this stuff.  If you find one, I would be quite interested.

